grat_hk_list:
Three good things from the past week:
1.  My granddaughter Emma graduated from high school and our whole family gathered to celebrate her together! The past year has been very hard for all of us, with her parents divorcing and we see her only half as much as ever before. My 99 year old Mom has dementia and she doesn’t see her grand kids or great grandkids often now… but we all came together and had a backyard bbq for our Emma… and being together without drama or sadness was glorious !!!
2.  Every morning I go to Moms at 8:30 and wake her up and get her showered and dressed for the day. This has been a struggle because she’s stubborn and often. Doesn’t want to get up yet, and I find myself getting angry at someone I love so much who isn’t herself anymore because of her dementia. I have stopped looking forward to this because it makes me feel so bad about myself. But in the past week, she has started to become used to her new routine and several times she was already awake! One day she thought it was Easter and another she greeted me with Merry Christmas…and I took a breath and let my frustration go and said Merry Christmas Mama…and we headed off for a shower talking about christmases past! It has been life changing! I felt proud of myself for being able to let go of my expectations of how she should be but can’t, and being able able to begin embracing this person who doesn’t remember yesterday but remembers everything about her childhood and mine. It’s the hardest thing I’ve ever done.
3.  I am retired from a medical office and the doctor I worked for for 30 years is dying. I have avoided going to see him because I love him and it’s so hard to see him like this. But last weekend I went and held his hand and he stared at me but maybe didn’t know me (again uncomfortable and hard for me) Toward then end of my visit his nurse was trying to get him to swish a medication around in his mouth and spit and he was swallowing it instead. She was angry at him, but he look at me and I said the name of the medication, and said to him “You used to prescribe that I
For our patients!” After a minute he smiled and spit… and squeezed my hand. Later when I was driving home I felt like I could fly I was so glad that I went! I’m going again this week!
